net.bytebuddy.instrumentation.method

Class MethodLookupEngine.Default.MethodBucket

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.bytebuddy.instrumentation.method.MethodLookupEngine.Default.MethodBucket
  • Enclosing class:
    MethodLookupEngine.Default

    protected static class MethodLookupEngine.Default.MethodBucket
extends Object
    A method bucket is used to identify unique methods of all super types and interfaces of a given type. A method bucket will therefore always filter any declared method of identical signature that was already added to the bucket by pushing a previous type. For this to work, a method bucket's methods must be invoked in a given order:
    1. A user needs to push all classes into the method bucket, beginning with the most specific class down to the Object class. By pushing classes first, interface methods can never override a method that was declared by a class.
    2. A user needs to push all interfaces that war registered on any of these classes into the bucket. The bucket will make sure that no interface is processed twice by remembering interfaces that were already pushed. The method bucket will furthermore process extension interfaces of any pushed interface. Whenever an interface method is registered, several possible scenarios can occur:
      1. A method of the interface was already declared by a class: These methods are always ignored.
      2. A method of the interface was already declared by a sub interface: In this case, the method.
